-- South African Stocks Gain for Third Day, Led by AngloGold and Woolworths
-- Janice Kew
-- 2010-06-17T16:14:07Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-17/south-african-stocks-gain-for-third-day-led-by-anglogold-and-gold-fields.html

          
          
             South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  advanced for a third trading day, climbing 116.31,
or 0.4 percent, to 27,799.03. The stock market was closed
yesterday for Youth Day national holiday.  
 The following are among the most active stocks in the South
African market today.  
 AngloGold Ashanti Ltd.  (ANG SJ), Africa’s largest gold
producer, rose 7.95 rand, or 2.4 percent, to 337 rand, its
biggest gain in almost three weeks.  Gold Fields Ltd. (GFI SJ) ,
Africa’s second-largest gold producer, increased 2.92 rand, or
2.8 percent, to 106.60 rand. The precious metal advanced on
concern that Europe’s financial turmoil will be prolonged,
boosting the appeal of gold as a store of value.  
 BHP Billiton Ltd.  (BIL SJ), the world’s largest mining
company, dropped for the first time in three days, losing 2.18
rand, or 1 percent, to 215.20 rand.  Anglo American Plc  (AGL SJ),
the diversified mining company that accounts for 10 percent of
the benchmark, declined 2.98 rand, or 1 percent to 300.78 rand.
Copper fell the most in almost two weeks, sliding as much as 3.6
percent to $6,410 a metric ton.  
 Woolworths Holdings Ltd.  (WHL SJ), the food and clothing
retailer, rallied 90 cents, or 3.6 percent, to 25.90 rand, the
biggest increase since May 10.  Truworths International Ltd.  (TRU
SJ), South Africa’s largest clothing retailer by market value,
gained 71 cents, or 1.3 percent, to 55.71 rand.  Massmart
Holdings Ltd.  (MSM SJ), the country’s biggest food and general-
goods wholesaler, advanced 1.65 rand, or 1.4 percent, to 121.40
rand.  
 Retail sales  rose for a fourth consecutive month in April,
advancing an annual 3.2 percent after climbing a revised 2.7
percent in March, Pretoria-based  Statistics South Africa  said on
its website today. The  median estimate  of 11 economists surveyed
by Bloomberg was for an increase of 2.1 percent.  
